\title{Solving Systems of Equations: Lesson Plan}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Briefly introduce the concept of systems of equations.
  \item Explain that a system of equations is a set of equations with multiple variables that need to be solved simultaneously.
  \item State the objective of the lesson: to learn how to solve systems of equations using the method of substitution.
\end{itemize}

\section{Background}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Review the concept of variables and equations.
  \item Discuss the importance of solving systems of equations in real-life situations.
  \item Introduce the method of substitution as a strategy for solving systems of equations.
\end{itemize}

\section{Problem Statement}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Present the problem: Given that $2x + 5y = 22$ and $3x + 2y = 11$, what is the value of $x$ and $y$?

  \item Discuss the importance of clearly defining the variables and the problem statement.
\end{itemize}

\section{Solution}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Step 1: Solve one equation for one variable in terms of the other variable.
  \item Step 2: Substitute the expression obtained in Step 1 into the other equation.
  \item Step 3: Solve the resulting equation for the remaining variable.
  \item Step 4: Substitute the value obtained in Step 3 back into one of the original equations to find the value of the other variable.
  \item Step 5: Check the solution by substituting the values of $x$ and $y$ into both original equations.
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Summarize the steps involved in solving systems of equations using the method of substitution.
  \item Emphasize the importance of checking the solution for accuracy.
  \item Provide additional practice problems for students to solve on their own.
\end{itemize}

\end{document}

